    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-11T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-11T12:00:00-05:00" n="129"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d129">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Eupropean War 1939/8959: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-11T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >March 11, 1941—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>483. In the course of a conversation with the German Ambassador last night he
                    said that he had heard the rumors current in Moscow that Germany contemplated an
                    attack on the Soviet Union and that he could categorically state that there was
                    “absolutely nothing to them.”</p>
                <p>The Rumanian Minister<note n="36" xml:id="d129fn36">Grigore Gafencu.</note> later
                    told me that after a long talk with the British Ambassador<note n="37"
                        xml:id="d129fn37">Sir Stafford Cripps.</note> yesterday, he had come to the
                    conclusion that the rumors of an impending German attack on the Soviet Union
                    were of British origin<note n="38" xml:id="d129fn38">For correspondence on the
                        wartime relations of Great Britain and France with the Soviet Union, see
                            <ref target="#pg_155">pp. 155</ref> ff.</note> and that they resulted
                    from “a stubborn continuation of the policy of wishful thinking which has
                    misguided the destinies of Britain for the past 5 years”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
